 where $\mathcal{T}_{ij}$ is the transported exposure of subsample $i$ for particle species $j$. This per-species normalization is required because photon and non-photon atmospheric streams have different sampling and exposure structures. The normalization check enforces $r_{\mathrm{event},j}\sum_i\mathcal{T}_{ij}=1$ for each particle species, so over-sampling changes the Monte Carlo variance but not the expected physical rate.
+
+As a reproducibility check, the selected prompt rate was reconstructed independently from the far-field source definitions and detector-level event weights. The check gives a selected $\wii$ prompt rate of $3.66\times10^{-2}\cps$, consistent with the prompt component used in Table~\ref{tab:primary_sensitivity}. The selected events from the positron-primary prompt stream were also traced in the event records; the 47 survivors in this stream are associated with annihilation-photon histories entering through the detector aperture. These checks support the source normalization and event provenance, but they do not add a new selection criterion.
 
